tive closure classes, which might require certain metadata. However, if method handles can’t find the class due to it being static or synthetic in Groovy 3, it complicates things, especially if the method might be hidden.\\n\\nAdding a compiled Groovy test isn’t an option, as tests are Java-only. I wonder if generating a small class with the same name as the active closure could work, but it may conflict with coverage expectations. I'll need to analyze more closely.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Addressing class file issues**\\n\\nI added a class file labeled \\\"active mapping,\\\" which feels like a step in the right direction. However, there might be some concern about a helper in the library package possibly violating the principle of keeping tests outside library packages. I hope any external ignores aren’t causing issues, but maybe the existing helpers ran into checkstyle problems. \\n\\nIf I use `MethodHandles.publicLookup`, that won’t work. I could try `java.lang.invoke` from the test package if it's allowed to access package-private classes. This could open new options!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating class version**\\n\\nI'm checking to confirm that we used class version 52. It should work, but there’s a possibility that the generated class didn’t declare `throws Throwable`—though that’s not strictly necessary. The test method does throw Throwable, which is good. I wonder if the issue arises from the generated class invoking a package-private method from a class in a different runtime package. Since they share the same package by binary name, access should be okay.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_Ea90yCf6YN8bxl5Xj1CbinpP|fc_09f42730d0c5f0df016a011761733c8190863c86dbe8d5b596", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/build.gradle", "edits": [{"oldText": "    outputs.file(generatedDirectAccessClasses.map { Directory directory ->\n        directory.file(\"io/restassured/int